There are currently no commercial options available to return to the UK from Nigeria. All airports in Nigeria are closed to international commercial flights until at least 4 June. If you cannot leave Nigeria at this time, see Staying during coronavirus.
UK special flights
The UK will operate special flights from Nigeria to the UK on the following dates:
1 June: Lagos – London
6 June: Abuja – London
8 June: Lagos – London
The flights cost £445.85 per person from Lagos and £600 per person from Abuja. The flight from Port Harcourt to London, via Abuja, also costs £600. Children under the age of 2 years old travel free of charge.
Booking for these flights is now closed. Seats on these flights have been assigned on a first come first served basis, with priority given to vulnerable travellers and those already on the waiting list. If you have been assigned a seat, we will contact you to confirm your booking, 48 to 72 hours ahead of your flight. Anyone not assigned a seat on any of these flights will get a full refund.
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British High Commission on Twitter @UKinNigeria and Facebook.
Eligibility
These flights are for:
British nationals, normally resident in the UK
dependants travelling with a British national normally resident in the UK
vulnerable British nationals will be prioritised
Vulnerable non-British UK residents with Indefinite Leave to Remain and other foreign nationals may be accommodated if there is sufficient capacity.
Eligibility will be checked before tickets are issued. Please therefore do not attempt to book if you do not meet the criteria above.
Travel to the airport
If you are assigned a seat on one of these flights you will need to make your own way to the airport. Please plan your journey in advance. After your seat is confirmed you will receive an email containing documents to help you pass through any checkpoints you encounter. You should not go to the airport unless your seat has been confirmed by email.
Your journey home
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
If you’re returning to the UK before 8 June, follow the current guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others. From 8 June there will be new rules for entering the UK. If your flight arrives on or after 8 June, you will need to follow the latest government guidance.
How to book
Booking for these special flights to return to the UK has now closed. Checks will be undertaken to confirm those who have booked meet the eligibility criteria for these flights. If people are found not to be eligible, seats will be made available to eligible travellers.
Future flight options
There are no further special charter flights planned from Nigeria to the UK after 8 June.
If you cannot leave Nigeria
If you cannot leave Nigeria at this time, see Staying during coronavirus.
Help and support
The best way to contact us for consular assistance is to use the contact form on our websites:
Abuja contact form
Lagos contact form
If you want to call instead, the numbers for assistance are:
Abuja: +234 (9) 462 3100
Lagos: + 234 (1) 277 0780/0781/0782
The High Commission cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone.
